title: For Sale:  FLARE GUN - M2 Aviators Set - UNUSUAL
postcontent:
This is quite unusual and you don't see these come up for sale complete very often. It's a M2 Flare Pistol Aviators Set consisting of the rather massive and super heavy duty M2 flare pistol (made by International Flare & Signal Company), carry case that holds the flare pistol and it's ammo supply which are absolutely massive MK1 60 second parachute flares. That's right 60 second parachutes!! To the best of my knowledge nothing else that is hand held rivals the sheer size and burn duration of these shells. They are monsters and each one weighs over 2 pounds! They are sealed on top and the primers are sealed as well. So while I can't guarantee it - I do think these big boys would fire if you decided to do that. Although you'd certainly need to pick your place well as you might have every emergency responder in the area show up if you don't. The flares were made by Kilgore and they are dated 1948. They are consecutively serial numbered so they are a matching set. This flare gun outfit might have seen military use or it could have been issued to a commercial flight crew. One thing for sure is that these were in service as the Cold War was heating up. The pistol, case and the flare cartridges are all in great shape. The carry case has the original nylon carry handle in place and the small strap that secures the pistol in it's compartment.
Call REDACTED

Made by Colt's Patent Fire Arms Manufacturing Co, Hartford, Connecticut. Six chambered long fluted cylinder with cylinder stops on outer surface, cylinder is a swing-out model to allow for loading and extraction, solid steel frame, steel rounded trigger guard, steel back strap, all metal components with excellent original bluing, the barrel was replaced and no rounds have been fired through it, fine wooden two-piece  grips. The Colt New Service model was the largest swing out-cylinder revolver made by Colt and appeared in 1898 and continued, various improvements and modifications, until 1944. Due to the period of its run, the model saw service in both World Wars and was produced in eighteen calibers, including popular British calibers to cater for the this market. This particular model is stamped with British ordnance marks and was chambered to the popular English .455 Eley. Army and Navy models were produced in 1909 and in the same year a now rare to find Marine Corp model was produced. O One-line Colt address stamped on barrel with second line of patent dates

title: For Sale:  BRAND NEW IN BOX
postcontent:
Okay, I have never posted a comment on Armslist, but my annoyance has been piqued.  Some people clearly do not understand basic definitions, so please allow me to clarify.

BNIB (Brand New In Box) means the weapon HAS NOT BEEN FIRED (apart from a test fire at the factory).  

ANY rounds through the weapon -- weather it is a box of ammo, a magazine (they are not "clips," folks), or a single round by a consumer -- means IT IS NO LONGER BRAND NEW!!  

Call it "Like New" if you like, but please don't call it new when it has been used, and please don't expect brand new prices for the weapon.

We live in a civil society; let's keep it that way.

Happy shooting!
